{"title_page": "Wild Kids", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Wild Kids\n| image                    = Wild-kids-bjornarnas-hus.jpg\n| image_size               = 200px\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = The home of Bj\u00f6rnarna (The Bears), the name of one of the teams in ''Wild Kids''.\n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = \n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = \n| developer                = \n| writer                   = \n| director                 = \n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = \n| voices                   = \n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = Sweden\n| language                 = Swedish\n| num_seasons              = \n| num_episodes             = \n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = \n| producer                 = \n| editor                   = \n| location                 = \n| cinematography           = \n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 2005, 2007, 2009, 2010, 2012-present\n| company                  = \n| distributor              = \n| channel                  = [[Sveriges Television|SVT]] (2005-2019) <br /> [[TV4 (Sweden)|TV4]] (2020-present)\n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| first_run                = \n| first_aired              = {{start date|df=y|2005|3|19}}\n| last_aired               = \n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = \n| website                  = \n| website_title            = \n| production_website       = \n| production_website_title = \n}}\n'''''Wild Kids''''' is a Swedish [[reality show]] for children currently airing on [[TV4 (Sweden)|TV4]]. The show aired for twelve seasons on [[Sveriges Television]] (SVT), between 2005 and 2019. [[Ola Lindholm]] was the host of the show for the first four seasons but was then replaced with [[Rickard Olsson]]. The second season was filmed in late 2006 and aired in early 2007.<ref name=\"GP\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gp.se/gp/jsp/Crosslink.jsp?d=907&a=278185 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829220425/http://www.gp.se/gp/jsp/Crosslink.jsp?d=907&a=278185 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-08-29 |title=Ola Lindholm tar \u00f6ver Kamratposten |date=2006-05-30 |work=[[G\u00f6teborgs-Posten]] |language=Swedish |accessdate=2009-08-26 }} </ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gp.se/gp/jsp/Crosslink.jsp?d=286&a=335090 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829220414/http://www.gp.se/gp/jsp/Crosslink.jsp?d=286&a=335090 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-08-29 |title=Wild kids tar paus - Ola Lindholm: \"Ren idioti\" |last=Bj\u00f6rnulfson |first=Jenny |date=2007-03-24 |work=[[G\u00f6teborgs-Posten]] |language=Swedish |accessdate=2009-08-27 }} </ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vt.se/nyheter/artikel.aspx?articleid=2065413|title=Tuffare bland de vilda barnen|last=Laquist|first=Erik|date=2007-02-07|work=V\u00e4sterviks-Tidningen |language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-08-28}}</ref> The show took a one-year break before returning in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gp.se/gp/jsp/Crosslink.jsp?d=907&a=469715 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829220430/http://www.gp.se/gp/jsp/Crosslink.jsp?d=907&a=469715 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-08-29 |title=Wild kids tuffare \u00e4n n\u00e5gonsin |date=2009-01-13 |work=[[G\u00f6teborgs-Posten]] |language=Swedish |accessdate=2009-08-28 }} </ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nt.se/noje/artikel.aspx?articleid=4126005|title=\"Wild kids\" \u00e5terv\u00e4nder med bajsregn|date=2008-08-28|work=[[Norrk\u00f6pings Tidningar]]|language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-08-28}}</ref> Except for 2006, 2008 and 2011, the show has been aired every year since its inaugural season. [[Carolina Kl\u00fcft]] took over the role as host in 2019. SVT then dropped off the rights for the show. For 2020, the 13th season, TV4 has taken over the rights for the show, leading to [[Linda Lindorff]] taking over the hosting role.\n\nDescribed as a children's version of ''[[Survivor (TV series)|Survivor]]'',<ref name=\"syd1\"/><ref name=\"syd2\"/> the show features two teams of children (\"Bj\u00f6rnarna\" and \"Lejonen\") competing with each other in competitions in the Swedish forest [[Kolm\u00e5rden]], where they live together until the show is over and the winners of the final win a trip to Africa.<ref name=\"syd1\">{{cite news|url=http://sydsvenskan.se/kultur-och-nojen/article75737/God-sapa-ska-tvatta-daligt-rykte.html|title=God s\u00e5pa ska tv\u00e4tta d\u00e5ligt rykte|last=Redvall|first=Eva|date=2004-08-14|work=[[Sydsvenskan]]|language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-08-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090830011845/http://sydsvenskan.se/kultur-och-nojen/article75737/God-sapa-ska-tvatta-daligt-rykte.html|archivedate=2009-08-30}}</ref> Unlike ''Survivor'', however, a new contestant joins the competition every week and no one gets sent home. The new contestant joins the team that won that week's competition. The goal is to have as many contestants as possible in one's team as it will give the team an advantage in competitions and eventually the final.<ref name=\"syd2\">{{cite news|url=http://sydsvenskan.se/kultur-och-nojen/ulfclaren/article95692/Expedition-Robinson-har-hittat-hem.html|title=Expedition: Robinson har hittat hem|last=Clar\u00e9n|first=Ulf|date=2005-05-09|work=[[Sydsvenskan]]|language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-09-02}}</ref>\n\n''Wild Kids'' won the [[Kristallen]] television award in 2007 for \"Children's Show of the Year\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://svt.se/2.62019/1.914067/utskriftsvanligt_format|title=Kristallregn \u00f6ver svenska tv-profiler|date=2007-09-17|publisher=[[Sveriges Television]]|language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-09-02}}</ref> The show has been considered a ratings success for SVT, and the episodes of the show's second season were viewed by approximately 625,000\u2013700,000 people.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kuriren.nu/nyheter/artikel.aspx?ArticleID=1714137|title=Os\u00e4ker framtid f\u00f6r SVT:s \"Wild kids\"|date=2007-03-25 |work=[[Norrbottens-Kuriren]]|language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\"Play\"/> In 2007, new episodes of ''Wild Kids'' received 200,000\u2013300,000 views every week on SVT's online channel [[SVT Play]], making it the channel's second most popular television show of the year.<ref name=\"Play\">{{cite news|url=http://svt.se/svt/jsp/Crosslink.jsp?d=3784&a=804329|title=Wild kids succ\u00e9 i SVT Play|date=2007-04-12|publisher=[[Sveriges Television]]|language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-09-02}}</ref>\n\nAround 10,000 Swedish children (ages 11-13) apply every year for one of the fourteen spots available on the show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pitea-tidningen.se/nara_dig/artikel.aspx?ArticleId=4366276|title=\"Wild kids\" tuffare \u00e4n n\u00e5gonsin|last=Milder|first=Julia|date=2007-01-15|work=Pite\u00e5-Tidningen|language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-09-02}}</ref> During one episode, a contestant saw her father choosing a new car over spending time with her. The girl burst into tears and although she got to see her father soon afterwards, the scene was heavily criticized by the Swedish media for treating the children too harshly. Lindholm defended the show by saying that the girl stopped crying quickly and the scene was heavily edited to make it seem worse than it actually was.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.journalisten.se/artikel/11936/hard-kritik-mot-svts-barnprogram-wild-kids|title=H\u00e5rd kritik mot SVTs barnprogram Wild Kids|last=Skagerberg|first=Karl|date=2006-10-17|work=Journalisten.se|language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-09-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090905165757/http://www.journalisten.se/artikel/11936/hard-kritik-mot-svts-barnprogram-wild-kids|archivedate=2009-09-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, an experimental reality show, ''Tittarnas Wild Kids'' (\"The Viewers' Wild Kids\"), aired for one season on SVT. The plot of the show was to let children from all of Sweden send a video where they carried out tasks to show knowledge within construction, animal spying, courage, nature, collaboration, strength and survival. Of the sent-in contributions, in each episode three finalists were chosen to go to Furuviksparken and carry out a real Wild Kids challenge. Ten episodes were produced, however the final two episodes were never broadcast since the show's presenter, [[Ola Lindholm]], got prosecuted (and later convicted) of [[narcotic]] misuse.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.gd.se/artikel/noje/svt-stoppar-tittarnas-wild-kids-2|title=SVT stoppar \"Tittarnas wild kids\"|accessdate=2019-01-24|date=2011-05-09|work=gd.se|language=sv}}</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://svt.se/wildkids ''Wild Kids''] on SVT's website\n*{{IMDb title|0467140}}\n\n[[Category:Sveriges Television programmes]]\n[[Category:Swedish reality television series]]\n[[Category:Swedish children's television series]]\n[[Category:2000s Swedish television series]]\n[[Category:2010s Swedish television series]]\n[[Category:2005 Swedish television series debuts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Wild Kids\n| image                    = Wild-kids-bjornarnas-hus.jpg\n| image_size               = 200px\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = The home of Bj\u00f6rnarna (The Bears), the name of one of the teams in ''Wild Kids''.\n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = \n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = \n| developer                = \n| writer                   = \n| director                 = \n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = 